Agreed. Concrete fix: wrap `JSON.parse` in `try/catch` and return a typed result envelope so callers can handle invalid input safely. Example:

```ts
export function parseInput<T>(raw: string):
  | { ok: true; data: T }
  | { ok: false; error: string } {
  try {
    return { ok: true, data: JSON.parse(raw) as T }
  } catch {
    return { ok: false, error: "Invalid JSON input" }
  }
}
```

Alternative: return `T | null` if you want a simpler API.

